Object.Field: LKM SQL to ADWC External Table
Logical schema for temporary file location

Specify the name of logical schema defining the location the temporary file will be stored before uploading to Object Storage. This must be a File technology logical schema. The temporary file will be stored on local file system where ODI agent is running.
Output format used for date datatypes. This format is following Java date/time fromat standards.
Output format used for time and timestamp datatypes. This format is following Java date/time fromat standards.
The number of rows (records read) requested by ODI agent on each communication with the data server.
Field separator character used in unloaded file.
SNP_TRT : LKM File to ADWC External Table

COMPONENT NAME: LKM SQL to ADWC External Table COMPONENT VERSION: 1 AUTHOR: Oracle COMPATIBILITY: ODI 12.2.1.4.0 or above
DESCRIPTION . This LKM will load data from SQL source to Oracle Autonomous Data Warehouse Cloud using Oracle Object Storage as intermediate staging. The result from SQL query is first loaded into Oracle Object Storage staging area. Then we are using External Table method to pull data from Object Storage. The user must set TEMP_OBJECT_STORAGE_SCHEMA and TEMP_FILE_SCHEMA KM option to designate temporary storage locations.
This LKM has to be used in combination with Oracle or generic SQL IKM.
Note : LKM SQL to ADWC External Table has two different sets of KM options for formatting date/time datatypes. 1. UNLOAD_DATE_FORMAT/UNLOAD_TIMESTAMP_FORMAT are used while unloading SQL query into text file. The formatting syntax is conform to Java Date and Time Patterns. 2. DATE_FORMAT is used while loading object storage text file into ADWC. The formatting syntax is conform to Oracle database syntax for formatting DATE datatype. If you are loading into TIMESTAMP column use Advanced option ADD_FORMAT_PROPERTIES to add timestampformat property.
It is very important to synchronize UNLOAD_DATE_FORMAT/UNLOAD_TIMESTAMP_FORMAT and DATE_FORMAT/timestampformat to use compatible format settings, even though they are using different syntax.
Here is an example of loading from source TIMESTAMP column into target TIMESTAMP column.
UNLOAD_TIMESTAMP_FORMAT = yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss.SSS ADD_FORMAT_PROPERTIES = 'timestampformat' VALUE 'YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS.FF3'
Also make sure that TIMESTAMP column precision allows for the given format to be stored.
